name.text: Constructing frequency tables and calculating mean and median

questiontext.text:
Mathematics test scores for \( {@n_students@} \) students in a class are listed below:

\({@raw_data@}\)

a) Complete the frequency distribution table below by counting the number of scores that fall into each class interval.

Class Interval Frequency
10 – 19[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]
20 – 29[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]
30 – 39[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]
40 – 49[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]
50 – 59[[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]
60 – 69[[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] [[feedback:prt6]]
70 – 79[[input:ans7]] [[validation:ans7]] [[feedback:prt7]]

b) Identify the Modal Class: [[input:ans8]] [[validation:ans8]] [[feedback:prt_mode]]

c) Using the table you created, calculate the following estimates (round to 2 decimal places):

  • Mean Score: [[input:ans9]] [[validation:ans9]] [[feedback:prt_mean]]
  • Median Score: [[input:ans10]] [[validation:ans10]] [[feedback:prt_median]]

generalfeedback.text:
a) Frequency Table Construction

To fill the table, we count how many scores appear in each interval. It helps to sort the data first:

{@raw_data_sorted@}

ClassMidpoint \( (x) \)Frequency \( (f) \)\( fx \)Cum. Freq \( (CF) \)
10-19{@midpoints[1]@}{@freqs[1]@}{@fx_list[1]@}{@cum_freqs[1]@}
20-29{@midpoints[2]@}{@freqs[2]@}{@fx_list[2]@}{@cum_freqs[2]@}
30-39{@midpoints[3]@}{@freqs[3]@}{@fx_list[3]@}{@cum_freqs[3]@}
40-49{@midpoints[4]@}{@freqs[4]@}{@fx_list[4]@}{@cum_freqs[4]@}
50-59{@midpoints[5]@}{@freqs[5]@}{@fx_list[5]@}{@cum_freqs[5]@}
60-69{@midpoints[6]@}{@freqs[6]@}{@fx_list[6]@}{@cum_freqs[6]@}
70-79{@midpoints[7]@}{@freqs[7]@}{@fx_list[7]@}{@cum_freqs[7]@}
Total{@sum_f@}{@sum_fx@}

b) Modal Class

The highest frequency is \({@max_freq@}\), which corresponds to the interval {@mode_str@}.

c) Estimated Mean and Median

Mean:

\( \bar{x} = \frac{\sum fx}{\sum f} = \frac{@sum_fx@}{@sum_f@} \approx \mathbf{@decimalplaces(mean_est, 2)@} \)

Median:

Position = \( \frac{N}{2} = \frac{@sum_f@}{2} = {@med_pos@} \). Looking at the CF column, the median lies in the {@lower_bounds[med_idx]@} - {@upper_bounds[med_idx]@} class.

\( Median = L + \left( \frac{\frac{N}{2} - CF_{prev}}{f_{med}} \right) \times h \) \( Median = {@L_med@} + \left( \frac{{@med_pos@} - {@cf_prev@}}{@f_med@} \right) \times {@class_width@} \) \( Median \approx \mathbf{@decimalplaces(median_est, 2)@} \)

questiondescription.text:
Daniel Murunga

In this question, you are required to organize a raw dataset of student scores into a frequency distribution table using specified class intervals. Based on this table, you must then identify the modal class and calculate estimates for the mean and median scores.
